gods.name: Hatmehit
gods.description: Fish goddess

gods.name: Aani
gods.description: A protector ape headed god

gods.name: Aati
gods.description: One of the 42 judges of the souls of the dead

gods.name: Am-heh
gods.description: A dangerous underworld god

gods.name: Amenhotep I
gods.description: The second king of the eighteenth dynasty, deified

gods.name: Amenhotep son of Hapu
gods.description: A scribe and architect in the court of Amenhotep III, later deified for his wisdom

gods.name: Amu-Aa
gods.description: A god who accompanies Osiris during the second hour of the night

gods.name: Andjety
gods.description: A god of the ninth nome of Upper Egypt

gods.name: Apedemak
gods.description: A warlike lion god from Nubia who appears in some Egyptian-built temples in Lower Nubia

gods.name: Apep
gods.description: A serpent deity who personified malevolent chaos and was said to fight Ra in the underworld every night

gods.name: Apis
gods.description: A live bull worshipped as a god at Memphis and seen as a manifestation of Ptah

gods.name: Arensnuphis
gods.description: A Nubian deity who appears in Egyptian temples in Lower Nubia in the Greco-Roman era

gods.name: Asclepius
gods.description: A Greek god worshipped in Egypt at Saqqara

gods.name: Ash
gods.description: A god of the Libyan Desert and oases west of Egypt

gods.name: Baal
gods.description: Sky and storm god from Syria and Canaan, worshipped in Egypt during the New Kingdom

gods.name: Babi
gods.description: A baboon god characterized by sexuality and aggression

gods.name: Banebdjedet
gods.description: A ram god, patron of the city of Mendes

gods.name: Ba-Pef
gods.description: A little-known underworld deity; ram-headed god of the eighth hour

gods.name: Bes
gods.description: Apotropaic god, represented as a dwarf, particularly important in protecting children and women in childbirth

gods.name: Buchis
gods.description: A live bull god worshipped in the region around Thebes and a manifestation of Montu

gods.name: Dedun
gods.description: A Nubian god, said to provide the Egyptians with incense and other resources that came from Nubia

gods.name: Dionysus-Osiris
gods.description: A life-death-rebirth god.

gods.name: Ha
gods.description: A god of the Libyan Desert and oases west of Egypt

gods.name: Ḥapy
gods.description: A son of Horus

gods.name: Hardedef
gods.description: Son of King Khufu who was deified after death because he wrote a book considered to be the work of a god

gods.name: Harmachis
gods.description: Sphinx god

gods.name: Haurun
gods.description: A protector and healing god, originally a Canaanite god

gods.name: Heka
gods.description: Personification of magic

gods.name: Heryshaf
gods.description: Ram god worshipped at Herakleopolis Magna

gods.name: Hu
gods.description: Personification of the authority of the spoken word

gods.name: Iah
gods.description: A moon god

gods.name: Ihy (Ihu)
gods.description: A child deity born to Horus and Hathor, representing the music and joy produced by the sistrum

gods.name: Imhotep
gods.description: Architect and vizier to Djoser, eventually deified as a healer god

gods.name: Kagemni
gods.description: A vizier to Sneferu who wrote the Instructions of Kagemni, later deified

gods.name: Kherty
gods.description: A netherworld god, usually depicted as a ram

gods.name: Kneph
gods.description: A ram creator god

gods.name: Mandulis
gods.description: A Lower Nubian solar deity who appeared in some Egyptian temples

gods.name: Mehen
gods.description: A serpent god who protects the barque of Ra as it travels through the underworld

gods.name: Mestȧ
gods.description: A son of Horus

gods.name: Min
gods.description: A god of virility, as well as the cities of Akhmim and Qift and the Eastern Desert beyond them

gods.name: Mnevis
gods.description: A live bull god worshipped at Heliopolis as a manifestation of Ra

gods.name: Nefertum
gods.description: God of perfume who was an aspect of Atum, but later became a separate deity

gods.name: Nehebu-Kau
gods.description: A protective serpent god

gods.name: Petbe
gods.description: God of revenge

gods.name: Ptah-hotep
gods.description: Writer of a Wisdom Text, later deified

gods.name: Qebeḥsenuf
gods.description: A son of Horus

gods.name: Qebui
gods.description: God of the north winds

gods.name: Reshep
gods.description: A Syrian war god adopted into Egyptian religion in the New Kingdom, depicted with beard and the crown of Upper Egypt

gods.name: Sah
gods.description: Personification of the constellation Orion

gods.name: Sebiumeker
gods.description: Guardian god of procreation and fertility, he was a major god in Meroe, Kush

gods.name: Seker
gods.description: God of the Memphite Necropolis and of the afterlife in general

gods.name: Serapis
gods.description: A Greco-Egyptian god from the Ptolemaic Period who fused traits of Osiris and Apis with those of several Greek gods. Husband of Isis who, like her, was adopted into Greek and Roman religion outside Egypt.

gods.name: Shed
gods.description: A god believed to save people from danger and misfortune

gods.name: Shezmu
gods.description: A god of wine and oil presses who also slaughters condemned souls

gods.name: Sia
gods.description: Personification of perception

gods.name: Sopd
gods.description: God of the eastern delta

gods.name: Sopdet (Sothis)
gods.description: Personification of the star Sirius, mother of Sopdu

gods.name: Ṭuamutef
gods.description: A son of Horus

gods.name: Tutu
gods.description: An apotropaic god from the Greco-Roman era

gods.name: Uneg/Weneg
gods.description: A plant god and son of Ra who maintains cosmic order

gods.name: Wepwawet
gods.description: A jackal god, the patron deity of Asyut, connected with warfare and the afterlife

gods.name: Yam
gods.description: A Syrian god of the sea who appears in some Egyptian texts

gods.name: Ammit
gods.description: Goddess who devoured condemned souls

gods.name: Astarte
gods.description: A warrior goddess from Syria and Canaan who entered Egyptian religion in the New Kingdom

gods.name: Ba'alat Gebal
gods.description: A Canaanite goddess, patroness of the city of Byblos, adopted into Egyptian religion

gods.name: Hatmehit
gods.description: Fish goddess worshipped at Mendes

gods.name: Hedetet
gods.description: A minor scorpion goddess

gods.name: Iabet
gods.description: Goddess of fertility and rebirth

gods.name: Iat
gods.description: A goddess of milk and nursing

gods.name: Ipy
gods.description: A mother goddess depicted as a hippopotamus

gods.name: Ishtar
gods.description: The East Semitic version of Astarte, occasionally mentioned in Egyptian texts

gods.name: Iusaaset (Ausaas)
gods.description: A female counterpart to Atum; a solar disc wearing goddess worshipped at Heliopolis

gods.name: Kebehut
gods.description: Daughter of Anubis, goddess of freshness, she helps him in mummifying dead bodies

gods.name: Mafdet
gods.description: A predatory goddess said to destroy dangerous creatures

gods.name: Mehet-Weret
gods.description: A celestial cow goddess

gods.name: Mehit
gods.description: A warrior lioness goddess originally from Nubia worshipped at Abydos, consort of Anhur

gods.name: Menhit
gods.description: A solar lioness goddess who personified the brow of Ra

gods.name: Meretseger
gods.description: A cobra goddess who oversaw the Theban Necropolis

gods.name: Meret
gods.description: The goddess of music who established cosmic order

gods.name: Meskhenet
gods.description: A goddess who presided over childbirth

gods.name: Nebethetepet
gods.description: A female counterpart to Atum

gods.name: Nefertari
gods.description: The mother of Amenhotep I, deified

gods.name: Nehmetawy
gods.description: A minor goddess, the consort of Nehebu-Kau or Thoth

gods.name: Perit
gods.description: A goddess of the underworld

gods.name: Qetesh
gods.description: A goddess of sexuality and sacred ecstasy from Syria and Canaan, adopted into Egyptian religion in the New Kingdom

gods.name: Raet-Tawy
gods.description: A female counterpart to Ra

gods.name: Renenet
gods.description: Goddess of fortune

gods.name: Renpet
gods.description: Goddess who personified the year

gods.name: Serket
gods.description: A scorpion goddess, invoked for healing and protection

gods.name: Seshat
gods.description: Goddess of writing and record-keeping, depicted as a scribe

gods.name: Shesmetet
gods.description: A lioness goddess

gods.name: Sopdet
gods.description: Deification of the star Sirius

gods.name: Ta-Bitjet
gods.description: A minor scorpion goddess

gods.name: Taweret
gods.description: Hippopotamus goddess, protector of women in childbirth

gods.name: Tayt
gods.description: Goddess of weaving

gods.name: Tenenet
gods.description: Goddess of brewing and protection

gods.name: Unut
gods.description: A goddess represented as a snake or a hare, worshipped in the region of Hermopolis

gods.name: Wepset
gods.description: A protector serpent goddess

gods.name: Werethekau
gods.description: A goddess who protected the king

gods.name: Hedjhotep
gods.description: God of fabrics and clothing

gods.name: Shai
gods.description: Personification of fate

gods.name: Aqen
gods.description: A deity of the underworld

gods.name: Medjed
gods.description: A minor god from the Book of the Dead.
